<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://everydaysexism.com/everyday-sexism/171582" title="R" rel="bookmark">R</a></h2> <section class="entry-meta">
<span class="author vcard"><a href="http://everydaysexism.com/author/everydaysexism" title="Posts by everydaysexism" rel="author">everydaysexism</a></span>
<span class="meta-sep"> | </span>
<span class="entry-date">10th May 2017</span>
</section></header>
<section class="entry-content">
<p>My (male) friend literally just compared me to a Trump supporter, because I am steadfast in my decision to never have children. Fuck everything. I want to die, I&#8217;m done with this entire world.</p>
<div class="entry-links"></div>
</section><footer class="entry-footer">
<span class="cat-links">Categories:<a href="http://everydaysexism.com/country/everyday-sexism" rel="category tag">Everyday Sexism</a></span>
<span class="tag-links"></span>
</footer> </article><article id="post-171583" class="post-171583 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-everyday-sexism">
<header>
<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://everydaysexism.com/everyday-sexism/171583" title="PeevedRightNow" rel="bookmark">PeevedRightNow</a></h2> <section class="entry-meta">
<span class="author vcard"><a href="http://everydaysexism.com/author/everydaysexism" title="Posts by everydaysexism" rel="author">everydaysexism</a></span>
<span class="meta-sep"> | </span>
<span class="entry-date">10th May 2017</span>
</section></header>
<section class="entry-content">
<p>(This is part-vent, as I am quite angry right now.) Working as the only female in a male-orientated team/traditional work culture.  Just had a meeting where someone used a variation of the &#8220;don&#8217;t worry your little head about it &#8211; your job is to make the tea&#8221; &#8216;Games People Play&#8217; ploy, when I raised a legitimate question arising from my role. No use escalating &#8211; my boss, who is male and also on these calls,  talks to me reasonably off-call and &#8216;gangs up with the boys&#8217; and is routinely  passive aggressive/ hugely patronising during the calls. On last Friday&#8217;s team call, his response to a process query was to explain, in painstaking detail, how to prioritise e-mails. I am a highly-qualified and experienced manager of 55.<br />
It is not safe to mention potential sexism or raise complaints and grievances in this culture as it brands you a trouble-maker and generates further openly-expressed or covert negative assumptions and decisions. There is lots of talk about how to get more women into the profession, which is worthwhile to consider, but this can only be a &#8216;band-aid over a gaping wound&#8217; and many women will leave if the underlying debilitating everyday sexism in all corporate cultures continues to remain unacknowledged and unaddressed.</p>
<div class="entry-links"></div>
