<section class="entry-content">
<p>Man grabbed my bum in a bar</p>
<div class="entry-links"></div>
</section><footer class="entry-footer">
<span class="cat-links">Categories:<a href="http://everydaysexism.com/country/everyday-sexism" rel="category tag">Everyday Sexism</a></span>
<span class="tag-links">Tags: <a href="http://everydaysexism.com/tag/public-space" rel="tag">Public space</a></span>
</footer> </article><article id="post-171591" class="post-171591 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-everyday-sexism">
<header>
<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://everydaysexism.com/everyday-sexism/171591" title="Kitty" rel="bookmark">Kitty</a></h2> <section class="entry-meta">
<span class="author vcard"><a href="http://everydaysexism.com/author/everydaysexism" title="Posts by everydaysexism" rel="author">everydaysexism</a></span>
<span class="meta-sep"> | </span>
<span class="entry-date">10th May 2017</span>
</section></header>
<section class="entry-content">
<p>I was watching an old episode of 999 on YouTube recently, where a British guy got stung by a swarm of bees. As part of this segment, a guy who was an expert (I think he was a lecturer) in beekeeping featured in the show, talking about bees &amp; beekeeping. He used the male pronoun to talk about beekeepers- because of course only men can be beekeepers! I&#8217;m sure there are quite a few female beekeepers out there!</p>
<div class="entry-links"></div>
</section><footer class="entry-footer">
<span class="cat-links">Categories:<a href="http://everydaysexism.com/country/everyday-sexism" rel="category tag">Everyday Sexism</a></span>
<span class="tag-links"></span>
</footer> </article><article id="post-171594" class="post-171594 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-everyday-sexism tag-relationships tag-university">
<header>
<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://everydaysexism.com/everyday-sexism/171594" title="Anonymous" rel="bookmark">Anonymous</a></h2> <section class="entry-meta">
<span class="author vcard"><a href="http://everydaysexism.com/author/everydaysexism" title="Posts by everydaysexism" rel="author">everydaysexism</a></span>
<span class="meta-sep"> | </span>
<span class="entry-date">10th May 2017</span>
</section></header>
<section class="entry-content">
<p>It was my freshman year of college, and I&#8217;d been dating this guy for about four or five months.  We were laying in bed in my dorm and he started to put his hand down my pants.  I told him that I wasn&#8217;t in the mood, but he kept going anyways, saying things like, &#8220;Oh come on, it&#8217;s not like you have to do anything,&#8221; or &#8220;What&#8217;s wrong with you?&#8221;  I didn&#8217;t know what to do, so I did nothing.  I started crying, quietly at first so he wouldn&#8217;t hear me, but soon it became loud and uncontrollable sobbing.  Only then did he stop.  But when he stopped, he didn&#8217;t apologize, he didn&#8217;t wipe my tears&#8230;  He just said &#8220;I can&#8217;t believe that you&#8217;re not into this,&#8221; and turned over in bed.</p>
<p>It wasn&#8217;t until several years later that I realized that I had been violated.  Until quite recently, I had thought that entire situation was my fault and that he had the right to be angry with me.  This is why sexism needs to stop.  It needs to stop so that the next girl who gets violated by her boyfriend knows that it&#8217;s not her fault.</p>
<div class="entry-links"></div>
